<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-8a-2-2">
	<statement>
		<p>
			 Let <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m>, and recall that <m>f</m> is only defined for <m>x \gt 0</m>.  As such, we can't consider the tangent line (or any other) approximation at <m>a = 0</m>.  Instead, we choose to work with an approximation to <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> centered at <m>a = 1</m> and will find the degree <m>4</m> Taylor polynomial approximation 
			 <me>
			 	T_4(x) = c_0 + c_1 (x-1) + c_2 (x-1)^2 + c_3(x-1)^3 + c_4(x-1)^4
			 </me>.
		</p>

			<ol marker="a.">
		      <li>
		        <p>
		          Determine <m>f'(x)</m>, <m>f''(x)</m>, <m>f'''(x)</m>, and <m>f^{(4)}(x)</m>, and then compute <m>f'(1)</m>, <m>f''(1)</m>, <m>f'''(1)</m>, and <m>f^{(4)}(1)</m>.  Enter your results in in <xref ref="T-8a-2-act-2-log">Table</xref>.
		        </p>	

		          <table xml:id="T-8a-2-act-2-log">
		            <title>Finding the derivatives of <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> at <m>a = 1</m>.</title>
